Original Problem

Below is a broken function for mapping services needed.

library(mosaic)
load("~/cvc-workshop/perpnew.Rda")

mapPriority <- function(data, sneed = "Medical", vari, colr = "red"){
  
  propneed <- data %>%
    filter(state != "N/") %>%
    group_by(state) %>%
    summarise(total = n(), need = sum(vari == "(1) Yes")) %>%
    mutate(prop = need/total)

  mUSMap(propneed, key="state", fill = "prop")+
    scale_fill_continuous(low="white", high = colr)+
    ggtitle(paste("Proportion of State", sneed, "Need"))

}

mapPriority(data = perpnew, sneed = "Medical", vari = "FU6P1", colr = "red")

Notice that even if we change the variable (FU6P1 to FU6P2), the map doesnâ€™t change.

mapPriority(data = perpnew, sneed = "Medical", vari = "FU6P2", colr = "red")

But if we add in the mutate_ function, it does change as expected.

mapPriority <- function(data, sneed = "Medical", vari, colr = "red"){
  
  propneed <- data %>%
    mutate_(vari=vari) %>%
    filter(state != "N/") %>%
    group_by(state) %>%
    summarise(total = n(), need = sum(vari == "(1) Yes")) %>%
    mutate(prop = need/total)

  mUSMap(propneed, key="state", fill = "prop")+
    scale_fill_continuous(low="white", high = colr)+
    ggtitle(paste("Proportion of State", sneed, "Need"))

}

mapPriority(data = perpnew, sneed = "Medical", vari = "FU6P2", colr = "red")

The title change and map color change now work fine.

The issue, as I understand it, is with getting summarise() to recogize â€œvariâ€ as a variable name in â€œdataâ€. The function summarise() is taking a standard function, n(), and a nonstandard function, sum(). Hypothetically, if we could use summarise_(sum(vari)) and summarise(n()) separately, weâ€™d be OK, but we cannot do that because we want to perform those two function on the same tbl.

Minimal Example with KidsFeet Data

Because the data from the original example isnâ€™t publically available, so weâ€™ll make a minimal reproducible example.

library(mosaic)

domRights <- function(df, var){
  
  df %>%
    group_by(sex) %>%
    summarise(sampsize = n(), rights = sum(var == "R"))
}

But itâ€™s fixed if we add the mutate_ function.

domRights <- function(df, var){
  
  df %>%
    mutate_(var=var) %>%
    group_by(sex) %>%
    summarise(sampsize = n(), rights = sum(var == "R"))
  
}

domRights(KidsFeet, "biggerfoot")

## 
##      sex sampsize rights
##   (fctr)    (int)  (int)
## 1      B       20      9
## 2      G       19      8
domRights(KidsFeet, "domhand")
## Source: local data frame [2 x 3]

##      sex sampsize rights
